1 empty:hidden first:pt-[1px]"><div class="markdown prose dark:prose-invert w-full break-words dark markdown-new-styling"><p data-start="0" data-end="57">You’re hitting a <strong data-start="17" data-end="50">module manifest compatibility</strong> issue.</p>
<p data-start="59" data-end="216">The error says <code data-start="74" data-end="86">RootModule</code> and <code data-start="91" data-end="113">CompatiblePSEditions</code> are invalid keys. That only happens when the importing session is <strong data-start="180" data-end="189">older</strong> than the manifest expects:</p>
<ul data-start="218" data-end="486">
<li data-start="218" data-end="280">
<p data-start="220" data-end="280"><code data-start="220" data-end="242">CompatiblePSEditions</code> is only valid in PowerShell <strong data-start="271" data-end="279">5.1+</strong>.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="281" data-end="486">
<p data-start="283" data-end="486"><code data-start="283" data-end="295">RootModule</code> isn’t recognized by <strong data-start="316" data-end="334">PowerShell 2.0</strong> (it uses <code data-start="344" data-end="361">ModuleToProcess</code>).<br data-start="363" data-end="366">
(PowerShell 4.0+ does support <code data-start="398" data-end="410">RootModule</code>, so if it’s complaining about <em data-start="441" data-end="447">that</em> you’re almost certainly in a v2 host.)</p>
</li>
</ul>
